Logistics:
  1. When will a formal code inspection be warranted?
  Formal code inspection is warranted when an issue of functionality is completed, but before merging the branch into main.

  2. Who will take the lead on moderating inspections?
  Any group members that didn't participate in authoring the code being inspected will take the lead when moderating inspection to allow for no bias.

  3. How will you share the results of inspections?
  The results of the inspections will be shared through GitHub pull requests.


  Criteria:
  4. What are the key "code smells" from each chapter of Clean Code? This is the big question. Chapter 17 of Clean Code might help you recall them.
  - Commented out code 
  - Too many arguments 
  - Insufficient tests (BVA no completed) 
  - Dead functions/code 
  - Multiple languages in one file
  - Nondescriptive variable/class names 
  - Incorrect or unimplemented behavior
  - Code duplication 
  - Code at the wrong level of abstraction
  - Obsolete and redundant comments 
  - Trainwrecks 
  - Classes with multiple responsibility 
  - Functions doing more than one thing 
  - Switch cases where polymorphism is possible 
  - Bad formatting/Inconsistent formatting 
  - Selector arguments 
  - Misplaced responsibility 
  - Magic Numbers 

  5. Will everyone apply all criteria from every chapter from Clean Code? Or will each person specialize in a few criteria?
  We will have each person specialize in a few criteria. Out split up will be the following:
  Jay:
   - Bad/Inconsistent formatting
   - Magic Numbers
   - Classes with multiple responsbility
   - Dead functions/code
   - Nondescriptive variable/class names
  Caleb:
   - Code duplication
   - Commented out code
   - Switch cases where polymorphism is possible
   - Misplaced responsibility
  Alex:
   - Functions doing more than one thing
   - Selector arguments
   - Obsolete and redundant comments
   - Insufficient tests
  Ethan:
   - Too many arguments
   - Trainwrecks
   - Multiple languages in one file
   - Code at the wrong level of abstraction


  Scope:
  6. Will your team inspect every file in your codebase? Every file you touch in your feature branch? Or something else entirely?
  Depending on the timing since the last code inspection, the files our team inspects will differ. Only the files that have been changed since the last review will be inspected.

  7. Of those files, will each person look at every file in consideration? Or will your team assign different files to different people?
  This goes with the answer to number 5, everyone will need to inspect all changed files to ensure that all criteria is met.


  Tools:
  8. To what extent can your inspection criteria be automated? Automation will increase your inspection's speed and reliability.
  A lot of the simple criteria can be spotted with spotbugs and the Google configuration for checkstyle linter.

  9. Which aspects of your inspection criteria will need human intervention?
  The more complex criteria such as coupling and cohesion. Also descriptive variable names, for example, because they are subjective.

